        ⊆
        A
        ×
        Z
        
           and 
        
        G
        ⊆
        B
        ×
        Z
        .
      
    
    {\displaystyle F\subseteq A\times Z{\text{ and }}G\subseteq B\times Z.}
   Jacques Riguet named these relations difunctional since the composition F GT involves univalent relations, commonly called partial functions.
In 1950 Rigeut showed that such relations satisfy the inclusion:
In automata theory, the term rectangular relation has also been used to denote a difunctional relation. This terminology recalls the fact that, when represented as a logical matrix, the columns and rows of a difunctional relation can be arranged as a block matrix with rectangular blocks of ones on the (asymmetric) main diagonal. More formally, a relation R on 
  
    
      
        X
        ×
        Y
      
    
    {\displaystyle X\times Y}
   is difunctional if and only if it can be written as the union of Cartesian products 
  
    
      
        
